title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson, S&W Model M&P 15 Sport 5.56mm 16" Barrel 811036 022188145663
postcontent: http://www.deguns.net/ProductDetails.asp?ProductCode=811036The M&P 15 lower and upper receivers are made from 7075 T6 Aluminum, fully forged in house by Smith & Wesson. Included with the lower: the single piece, solid forged, non-removable, over sized for gloves trigger guard. A typical six position telescoping stock is standard, along with sling mounts allowing for single or double point sling attachment. There is even a bayonet lug just in case. All of the M&P15 Sport’s parts are interchangeable with the rest of their AR15 product line.The M&P15 Sport’s barrel isn’t an M4 cut. This cut in the barrel will allow to mount a M203 grenade launcher. This additional cut also does not help the harmonics of the barrel. We think this a advantage that will help accuracy but will ultimately come down to the ammo used. The Smith sports a full profile barrel of American 4140 Steel. The bolt carrier and gas key are chromed, and the barrel sports their Melonite coating. Smith claims that the bare bones approach has no effect on durability. There have been reviews with this rifle firing 85,000 rounds of various brands of ammunition without any visible damage to the Melonite finish. We have found this to be a very reliable platform and so have law enforcement and countless other agencies. The engineers at Smith and Wesson made a great call when deciding to reduce the cost of their AR15 by not including a forward assist most shooters don’t use forward assists often, and when they do, it can lead to a dangerous situation. When using a forward assist, there is a potential for an inexperienced shooter to use the forward assist to jam the bolt forward when it is not the right response to a jam. A forward assist on any AR15 could cause the cartridge to get super stuck in the rifle. The original Mil Spec on the AR-15 did not include the forward assist. Smith and Wesson made another good call deciding not adding a dust cover to their M&P Sport AR15. Most AR15 shooters have little or no need for a dust cover because they’re firing from safe and clean environments. The M&P Sport is mostly used at shooting ranges, hunting, etc. In this day and age everyone is looking for the best value out there and with out any doubt this is it, you are defiantly not paying for any unneccessary features on this model. 30 Round PMAG MagazineAdjustable Front and Rear Sights6-Position Telescopic Butt StockChrome-lined Gas Key and Bolt Carrier16" Barrel 1 in 9” 4140 Steel 5.56 mm NATOReceiver 7075 T6 Aluminum Hard Coat Black AnodizedUPC: REDACTED63MFG: 811036

title: For Trade:  Walther P99 AS 9mm (The Bond Gun) TRADES WANTED!
postcontent:
I am looking to trade a Walther P99 AS in 9mm; yes, the Bond gun. This is a recent production gun that has the updated rail and no hump in the middle of the trigger guard. This gun has had 500 rounds through it. Gun comes with factory box, paperwork, test target and two 15-round mags. I also have four more factory 15-round mags and four 20-round magazines. That's a total of 10! These beautiful, blued, reliable OEM mags were made by Mec-Gar for Walther.

The "AS" pistols give the shooter 3 trigger modes to choose from. They can be fully decocked into DA/SA mode (striker down). The gun can also be left pre-cocked after chambering, leaving the trigger in AS mode (SA trigger with light take up). The gun can also be placed in fully cocked mode for a short, crisp trigger pull with a light reset (think Glock, M&P, PPQ, etc.). It has adjustable sights and interchangeable backstraps. These guns were way ahead of their time, and in some ways they still are. These guns are triple proof marked and their build quality rivals that of H&K.

The P99s can usually be had for just under $600. There's close to $300 in additional mags here, which you can see for yourself if you shop around.

I'm looking to trade this pistol face-to-face in Tampa Bay.
